---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="Body Weight: Should You Track in kg or lbs?" description="Track body weight in kg or lbs? Compare precision, ease of tracking, and which unit works better for fitness goals." keywords="body weight kg or lbs, weight tracking, fitness weight, metric vs imperial weight, weight loss tracking, body weight measurement, scale units">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Weight</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="Body Weight: Should You Track in kg or lbs?" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 10, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>When you step on a scale, does it matter whether you read 75 kg or 165 lbs? For most people the number is just a reference point, but the unit you choose can actually affect how you perceive your progress. Here is a closer look at both options.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Case for Kilograms</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Smaller numbers</strong> — your weight in kg is about half the lbs figure, which some people find less daunting</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Decimal precision</strong> — most metric scales show 0.1 kg increments (100 g), giving you fine-grained tracking</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Scientific standard</strong> — research papers, nutrition databases, and medical records use kilograms</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Simpler math</strong> — calculating BMI and medicine dosages is easier in kg</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>International</strong> — used by the vast majority of the world</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Case for Pounds</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Larger numbers show smaller changes</strong> — losing 1 lb sounds achievable (it is about 450 g)</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Familiar in the US</strong> — gym equipment, food labels, and conversation all use pounds</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Half-pound increments</strong> — many US scales show 0.2 lb steps, which is comparable precision to 0.1 kg</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Cultural context</strong> — if everyone around you speaks in pounds, switching creates a communication gap</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Which Shows Progress Better?</h2>
      <p>A common argument is that pounds "show more progress" because a 5-pound loss sounds larger than a 2.3 kg loss — even though they are the same thing. Psychologically, seeing a bigger number decrease can be motivating for some people.</p>
      <p>On the other hand, tracking in kilograms with one decimal place gives you 10 data points per kilogram, which means you can detect trends earlier without the emotional rollercoaster of whole-number jumps.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">Pro Tips for Weight Tracking</h2>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Pick one unit and stick with it</strong> — switching between systems makes it harder to spot trends</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Weigh at the same time daily</strong> — morning, after bathroom, before eating gives the most consistent readings</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Track weekly averages</strong> — daily fluctuations of 1-2 kg (2-4 lbs) are completely normal due to water and food</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">
          <span class="text-green-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span>
          <span><strong>Use a trend line</strong> — apps that smooth your data reveal the real direction regardless of daily noise</span>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-1">The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>Neither unit is objectively better. Use whichever feels natural and motivating to you. What matters is consistency in measurement conditions, not the unit on the display. If you ever need to convert between systems for a doctor, gym, or app, our weight converter handles it instantly.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/weight" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Weight Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/weight" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
